Cache identical calls so you pay once. LangChain has a built-in LLM cache (set_llm_cache with SQLiteCache or in-memory). With the same prompt + params, the first call hits OpenAI and every repeat is free. This alone is huge when you re-run a test suite, since most calls are identical across runs.
Record once, replay forever (the big one for test suites). Use VCR-style cassettes — vcrpy or the pytest-recording plugin — to capture real HTTP responses on the first run and replay them from disk after that. Your tests then run offline, deterministically, and at zero cost. You only re-record when a prompt or model genuinely changes. This is the single most effective pattern for "I want to test lots of cases repeatedly."
Mock the LLM entirely where you're testing logic, not model output. LangChain ships FakeListLLM / FakeListChatModel / GenericFakeChatModel that return scripted responses. For LangGraph specifically, most of what you're testing is graph wiring — routing, state transitions, conditional edges, retries — not the model's prose. Swap in a fake model for those, and you can assert on control flow for free. Reserve real calls for the handful of tests that actually validate prompt quality.
Use a cheaper model for the bulk of runs. Develop and iterate against gpt-4o-mini (or the cheapest model that exercises the same code paths), and reserve the expensive model for a final, smaller validation pass. The structure of your graph behaves the same; you're just paying far less per token while iterating.
Shrink and cap what you do send. Set max_tokens on outputs so a runaway response can't drain credits, trim prompts to the minimum that reproduces the case, and prune conversation state in long LangGraph runs so you're not resending accumulated history every node.
Run real-API tests deliberately, not by default. Mark them (@pytest.mark.llm or similar) and exclude them from the normal loop, so your fast inner loop is fully mocked/replayed and you only spend credits when you explicitly opt in.
A practical layering that works well: fake models for graph-logic tests → cached/replayed cassettes for integration tests → a small, gated set of live calls against the real model for final validation. You get to test hundreds of cases continuously while real spend stays near zero.
